#   GET-009: efficient beagleâ†”beagle (`be://`) sync â€” reachability-based upload-pack, cross-file serving, redundant-pack GC

Make `be://` keeper-to-keeper sync as efficient as git's own transport: the serving keeper should ship *only the objects the requesting keeper lacks*, across any number of pack files and divergent branches, and never let a shard accumulate duplicates. This is the umbrella ticket for the beagle-side upload-pack; [GET-007] landed the first increment (`5124b2ee`: `wire_locate_sha` resolves to the LATEST copy, so the byte-offset watermark stops re-shipping duplicate tails for the common linear/dup-reingest case), but the watermark model is structurally a single contiguous byte-range of one log file â€” it cannot do reachability across files or exclude duplicates mid-range. The remaining work is to replace it with true object-level negotiation and to reclaim already-bloated shards. This is a `be://`-only concern: fetches from a git remote (`ssh:`/`https:`) use real `git-upload-pack` reachability and are unaffected. See [GET], [POST], [GET-007], [CLAUDE].

##  Issues
The beagle upload-pack (`keeper/WIRE.c` `WIREBuildSegments`/`WIREServeUpload`) prunes by a byte-offset watermark over one pack-log file, not by object reachability.

 -  *No reachability exclusion.* The server ships a contiguous range `[watermark .. end_offset)` of one `.keeper` file; it has no notion of `closure(wants) âˆ’ closure(haves)`. Any duplicate or unrelated object inside that range is shipped regardless of whether the client has it. [GET-007]'s latest-copy fix tightens the *anchor* but not the *model*.
 -  *Cross-`file_id` haves are dropped.* `if (hfid != want_fid) continue` (`WIRE.c:283`) ignores a have in a different pack-log file, and the file-open hardcodes the trunk file (`WIRE.c:308`, `wire_pack_path(â€¦, want_fid)`) â€” "multi-shard tba". A client whose common ancestor lives in an older `file_id` than the want gets no anchor â†’ whole-log ship.
 -  *Divergent multi-branch histories.* A single max-watermark can't express "ship branch B's objects minus what the client has from branch A"; interleaved per-branch packs defeat one byte range.
 -  *Already-bloated shards never shrink.* A shard that accumulated duplicates before [GET-007] (e.g. a 498 MB pack of 290,853 objects ~14Ã— a fresh clone) stays bloated â€” there is no redundant-pack GC/compaction. The append-only log needs a compaction pass that rewrites a shard to one deduplicated pack.
 -  *Protocol is MVP.* `WIREServeUpload` sends one `NAK` then the pack (no `multi_ack`/`ACK common`), so the client cannot iteratively narrow the common set; the haves are a one-shot best-effort list capped at `WIRE_MAX_HAVES`.

##  Blockers
The keeper pack log is append-only; a reachability serve must build a fresh pack of only-missing objects (it cannot rely on a contiguous byte range). GC/compaction must also stay append-only-safe (write a new compacted pack/shard, swap, never mutate a live one mid-read). Decide whether to reuse git's pack-objects-style closure or implement over the keeper's LSM index + commit walk.

##  Planned
Replace the offset watermark with object-level negotiation; add cross-file serving and a compaction pass. Stage it.

 -  *St.1 (landed, [GET-007] `5124b2ee`):* latest-copy `wire_locate_sha` so the watermark stops re-shipping duplicate tails on a clean linear log; re-fetch of an unchanged repo ships ~0. Regressions `keeper/test/WIREREFETCH` + `WIREE2EREFETCH`.
 -  *St.2 â€” reachability serve:* rewrite `WIREBuildSegments`/`WIREServeUpload` to compute `closure(wants) âˆ’ closure(haves)` using the existing `KEEPIsAncestor`/`KEEPEmitCommitsSince`/`WALKTree` primitives and emit a freshly-built pack of exactly the missing objects (handle thin-pack delta bases the client already has). Repro: divergent two-branch peers fetch only the disjoint objects; cross-`file_id` ancestor have prunes correctly. Drop the byte-watermark path once covered.
 -  *St.3 â€” redundant-pack GC/compaction:* an offline pass (`be gc`? a keeper maintenance verb) that rewrites a bloated shard into one deduplicated pack (dedup by full sha, not 60-bit hashlet â€” avoid the silent-drop risk noted in [GET-007]), append-only-safe (new shard, atomic swap). Repro: a polluted shard compacts back toward fresh-clone size.
 -  *St.4 (optional) â€” `multi_ack`/`ACK common`* so large divergent fetches narrow iteratively instead of one-shot.
 -  Metric/guard: a `be://` re-fetch transfers object-count â‰ˆ git's minimal set; a fresh `be://` clone's shard â‰ˆ a fresh git clone's `.git`; assert in a load test. Update `keeper/INDEX.md`.
 -  Note: the [GET-007] held ingest-dedup band-aid (60-bit-hashlet decide-before-append) is SUPERSEDED by reachability serving and stays dropped (silent-drop tail risk).

